passages.text: Asia ex- Japan Equity Strategy (Rajiv Batra/Mixo Das/Wendy Liu/Khoi Vu, CFA)

Our aggregate measure of investor positioning in Asia now sits around the 85th %ile (having gone as high as 97 th %ile in July - Figure 1). While this would normally be considered a significant headwind, the global policy easing and China liquidity surge currently underway is providing a strong counter force. In this context, we believe the equity bull market will remain intact and any correction/consolidation will present a buying opportunity. However, it is important to manage risks where positioning is particularly crowded. Looking across LO, HF and Quant investors, we note the highest crowding in Taiwan Tech/Semis and Indo Financials, followed by China Growth stocks (semis, consumer and biotech). Alongside this, ongoing support from monetary policy should eventually warrant a widening of the leadership and outperformance of Cyclicals. We are upgrading the Materials sector to Ow in the AxJ region following our recent allocation changes in India (see report). Within the AxJ region, our pecking order is Korea > India > China > Taiwan > ASEAN. Our key OwS are: China Tech, Internet, Healthcare, Materials, select Financial/Industrials; India Financials, Consumer ex Auto, Materials, Real Estate, Hospitals, select power/defense; Korea Financials, Tech, Holdco; TSMC in Taiwan; and ASEAN Financials, Real Estate, Utilities, Healthcare, IT.
Asian Tech (Gokul Hariharan/Albert Hung)
Key takeaways from NVDA 2QFY26 results for Asian Tech are as below:

Neutral result and guidance: NVIDIA reported total revenue of \(46.7 billion for the July quarter, exceeding its guidance, but largely in line with market expectations. Sequential growth was seen across all market platforms in 2QFY26. The company guided to sequential growth for 3QFY26. Data Center revenues were up 56% YoY and 5% QoQ, driven by the strength of the Blackwell platform (grew 17% QoQ), coupled with continued increase in H100 and H200 shipments. 3Q guidance suggests a neutral stance, with revenue guidance of\) 54 bn +/- 2%, implying 13- 18% QoQ growth, in line with JPME and Consensus. However, guidance for the October quarter does not include any H20 shipments to China, reflecting ongoing geopolitical uncertainties.

Potentially taking a breather; our thoughts on what comes next after the recent rally... Both CCL and PCB sectors have seen very robust share price moves in the past weeks (MTD shares up 20- 25% for the major names; vs. 3% for Taiex), driven by increasing discussions of supply tightness, plus the concerns for rising raw material supplies tightness (copper foil, glass fiber, etc) in the coming year. Across the board, the shares are trading at practically all- time high multiples since early 2023 (the

inception of Al boom). While we expect the tightness for PCB and CCL to continue in the coming year (and likely beyond) on robust spec migration, we do wish to highlight that a potential moderation in rerating could take place in the next 1- 3 months. Nevertheless, we suggest investors should still accumulate high quality names like EMC on pullbacks as the long term outlook remains compelling.
Hua Nan FHC (Jemmy S Huang) (2880 TT, UW, PT NT\$24.60)

HNFHC's 1H25 results came in slightly ahead of our estimates, as better- than- expected earnings growth at the banking operations was partially offset by an earnings decline at the securities and P&C insurance operations. We revise up our FY25/26E earnings by \(10\% /14\%\) to factor in lower credit costs but retain our UW rating with a new PT of NT\$24.6 by moving forward our valuation base to Dec- 26 and factoring in stock dividends.
Silergy Corp (William Yang) (6415 TT, OW, PT NT\$500.00)

Silergy reported its 2Q25 earnings on 28 Aug with a miss. The company will host an earnings call on 29 Aug after market close. In this note, we revise down our 2025 YoY growth estimate to factor in demand slowdown given tariff- driven costs and geopolitical concerns. However, we believe the weaker 2025 growth is well- known to the market and demand should gradually pick up in 2H25. For 2026, we see stronger growth potential from its automotive business, driven by meaningful content value increases from new products (e.g. MCU). Also, its server business may have some breakthroughs with new chip customer's adoption. Thus, we keep OW as we think investors will start to focus more on Silergy's longer- term outlook.
